headline: BYD Hits Sales Goal, Set to Topple Tesla as Biggest EV Maker
summary: The Shenzhen-based carmaker delivered 4.6 million vehicles last year, up 7.7% from 2024.  Tesla on Friday is expected to report that it delivered around 440,900 vehicles in the fourth quarter, down 11% from a year earlier, according to data compiled by Bloomberg.  An influx of new models is also making domestic competition even fiercer, while trade barriers pose challenges for BYD’s ambitions to expand overseas.

headline: Samsung Electronics says customers praised competitiveness of HBM4 chip
summary: Samsung Electronics customers have praised the differentiated competitiveness of its next-generation high-bandwidth memory (HBM) chips, or HBM4, saying "Samsung is ​back", co-CEO and chip chief Jun Young-hyun said in a New Year address.  In October, ‌Samsung said it was in "close discussion" to supply its HBM4 to U.S. artificial intelligence leader Nvidia, as the South Korean ‌chipmaker scrambles to catch rivals including compatriot SK Hynix in AI chips.  "On HBM4 in particular, customers have even stated that 'Samsung is back'," Jun said in remarks reviewed by Reuters, adding that the company still had work to do to further improve competitiveness.

headline: Tesla loses title as world's biggest electric vehicle maker as sales fall for second year in a row

headline: Tesla Q4 Vehicle Deliveries Fall 16%. Miss Already Low Expectations.
summary: Tesla delivered 418,227 electric vehicles in the fourth quarter, down 15.6% from 495,570 in Q4 2024. However, TSLA shares angled higher before Friday' stock market open. The EV giant reported Friday that fourth-quarter deliveries included 406,585 Model 3 and Model Y EVs, as well as 11,642 "other" vehicles, which include the Model S, Model X and Cybertruck.
